    ],
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 2, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧨 GPT-5.5 just made the cyber benchmark discourse less comforting\n\nThe lab scorecard has acquired a small flashing red light. Naturally, it came with percentages.\n\n- **The test:** the UK AI Security Institute said on April 30 that GPT-5.5 is the second model to complete one of its multi-step cyber-attack simulations end-to-end.\n- **The numbers:** GPT-5.5 scored 71.4% on AISI's Expert cyber tasks, versus 68.6% for Claude Mythos Preview, 52.4% for GPT-5.4, and 48.6% for Opus 4.7.\n- **The practical detail:** in one Rust VM reverse-engineering task, GPT-5.5 solved in 10 minutes and 22 seconds at $1.73 of API cost; AISI estimated an expert human needed roughly 12 hours.\n\n*The scary part is not one model. It is that two different labs are now landing in the same danger zone.*\n\n**Sources:** [AISI evaluation](https://www.aisi.gov.uk/blog/our-evaluation-of-openais-gpt-5-5-cyber-capabilities) | [Ars Technica](https://arstechnica.com/ai/2026/05/amid-mythos-hyped-cybersecurity-prowess-researchers-find-gpt-5-5-is-just-as-good/)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 SoftBank wants Roze to build data centers with robots and a $100B sticker\n\nMasayoshi Son looked at the AI infrastructure bill and apparently decided the shovel should get its own IPO.\n\n- **The plan:** Reuters, citing the Financial Times, reported on April 30 that SoftBank plans to create and list Roze, a U.S.-based AI and robotics company focused on building data centers.\n- **The ambition:** executives are reportedly aiming for a $100 billion valuation and a listing as early as 2026.\n- **The backdrop:** SoftBank is already leading financing for Stargate, has commitments around OpenAI, and owns robotics exposure through ABB's robotics business and DigitalBridge.\n\n*The AI boom has reached the stage where the construction crew is also a venture-scale thesis.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters via Investing.com](https://m.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/softbank-plans-to-list-new-ai-and-robotics-company-in-us-ft-reports-4647497?ampMode=1) | [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/softbank-plans-robotics-and-ai-firm-in-the-us-to-build-data-centers-aims-for-usd100-billion-valuation-and-an-ipo-this-year)\n\n---\n\n## 🎛️ Claude got plugged into the creative toolchain and called it taste support\n\nThe assistant wars have moved from chat boxes to whatever file is currently ruining a designer's afternoon.\n\n- **The rollout:** Anthropic announced Claude for Creative Work on April 28, adding connectors for Adobe, Ableton, Affinity by Canva, Autodesk Fusion, Blender, Resolume, SketchUp and Splice.\n- **The Adobe bite:** the Adobe connector gives Claude access to more than 50 Creative Cloud tools, including Photoshop, Premiere and Express.\n- **The Blender angle:** the Blender connector exposes a natural-language interface to Blender's Python API, and Anthropic says the MCP-based integration remains accessible to other LLMs too.\n\n*The agent layer is no longer asking for assets. It is asking for the project file and a chair at the production meeting.*\n\n**Sources:** [Anthropic](https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-for-creative-work?c=ordem) | [TechRadar](https://www.techradar.com/pro/claude-cant-replace-taste-or-imagination-but-it-can-open-up-new-ways-of-working-anthropic-signs-up-adobe-blender-and-more-to-push-claude-into-creative-work)\n\n---\n\n## 🏗️ Big Tech's AI capex plan has crossed the $700B line and kept walking\n\nApparently the answer to capacity constraints is a number large enough to make depreciation sweat.\n\n- **The total:** Bloomberg reported on April 30 that the largest U.S. tech firms now plan up to $725 billion in 2026 capital spending, mostly for AI data-center equipment.\n- **The split:** Microsoft set calendar-year capex at $190 billion, Alphabet is in the same zone, Amazon stayed near $200 billion, and Meta raised its forecast again.\n- **The component tax:** Tom's Hardware reported that Microsoft attributed $25 billion of its capex budget to rising memory and component costs.\n\n*AI is still software, sure. It just happens to arrive on a power bill with a balance sheet attached.*\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-30/us-big-tech-ratchets-up-ai-spending-past-700-billion-this-year) | [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/big-tech/big-techs-ai-spending-plans-reach-725-billion)\n\n---\n\n## 🕵️ Senators asked nine AI labs how China-proof their vaults really are\n\nModel security has reached the awkward part where the threat model includes employees, contractors and privileged access.\n\n- **The letters:** on May 1, Chuck Grassley and Jim Banks pressed OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, xAI, Meta, Microsoft, Amazon, Safe Superintelligence and Thinking Machines Lab on PRC espionage safeguards.\n- **The checklist:** they asked about insider-threat detection, personnel vetting, access to model weights or adjacent assets, and when companies would notify the U.S. government about a security threat.\n- **The deadline:** Axios reported that the companies were asked to respond to nine questions by May 20.\n\n*The AI race is now a lab-security problem with congressional stationery attached.*\n\n**Sources:** [Senate Judiciary Committee](https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/press/rep/releases/grassley-banks-press-american-ai-companies-on-chinese-espionage-safeguards) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/04/29/ai-firms-china-congress)\n\n---\n\n## 🧳 AI export controls are taking a field trip to Silicon Valley\n\nWashington would like to know whether the companies selling the stack can also help police the stack. Cute timing.\n\n- **The trip:** Axios reported on May 1 that House Foreign Affairs Committee members will meet Silicon Valley companies next week to discuss AI and export controls.\n- **The guest list:** Google, Anthropic, Meta, Tesla, Intel, Applied Materials and NVIDIA are among the companies expected in the conversations.\n- **The policy hook:** the committee advanced the MATCH Act earlier in April, targeting China's access to tools for manufacturing advanced chips.\n\n*The control point is no longer only the border. It is the vendor roadmap, the chip toolchain and the sales process.*\n\n**Sources:** [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/05/01/house-foreign-affairs-silicon-valley-ai-exports) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/us-targets-chinese-chipmaking-with-proposed-export-restrictions-on-asml-and-others-4597014)\n\n---\n\n## 🧬 Cursor and Airbnb got pulled into the Chinese-model dependency file\n\nCheap models were fun right up until a House committee started reading the supplier list out loud.\n\n- **The probe:** House Homeland Security and the Select Committee on China announced on April 29 a joint investigation into U.S. adoption of PRC-developed AI models.\n- **The targets:** the first letters went to Anysphere over Cursor's Composer 2 reportedly being built on Moonshot AI's Kimi, and to Airbnb over customer-service use of Alibaba's Qwen.\n- **The claim:** the committees said PRC-developed models grew from about 1% of global AI workloads in late 2024 to a reported 30% by the end of 2025.\n\n*The supply-chain question is now: not just whose cloud, but whose model sits inside the workflow.*\n\n**Sources:** [House Homeland Security Committee](https://homeland.house.gov/2026/04/29/chairmen-garbarino-moolenaar-announce-joint-investigation-into-national-security-risks-posed-by-prc-ai-models/) | [Nextgov/FCW](https://www.nextgov.com/artificial-intelligence/2026/04/house-panels-probe-airbnb-anysphere-over-use-chinese-ai-models/413207/)\n\n---\n\n## 🚗 Connected cars got filed under rolling surveillance software\n\nThe car is now a computer, the computer has radios, and Congress has finally found the settings menu.\n\n- **The bill:** Senators Bernie Moreno and Elissa Slotkin introduced the Connected Vehicle Security Act of 2026 to ban imports, sales and operation of vehicles made in China or other countries of concern.\n- **The software angle:** the proposal also bars Chinese-developed connected-vehicle technologies, including software and data systems, from American roads.\n- **The coalition:** General Motors and the CAR Coalition backed the legislation, framing it as supply-chain and industrial-security policy.\n\n*The geopolitics is real, but the object is still software on wheels. Into AIz it goes.*\n\n**Sources:** [Senator Bernie Moreno](https://www.moreno.senate.gov/press-releases/moreno-slotkin-bill-to-ban-chinese-vehicles-connected-components-from-u-s-market/) | [Autos Innovate](https://www.autosinnovate.org/posts/press-release/statement-on-moreno-slotkin-chinese-vehicle-ban)\n"
  }
]
